[In pencil: Hulett, Irene, no date]
Dear Mr. Conroy,
I saw your book (The Jack Conroy Reader) in our local library. I had never heard of you but that's not a big surprise because I hated reading until a short time ago. I must say I enjoy your writting style. I wish I would have heard of you sooner.
Now the reason I'm writting. In the story Boyhood in a Coal Town you stated some things that got my attention. First off your name is the reason I picked up this book. My fathers name is John Conroy. Than when I read your father

was a French speaking Canadian I just had to write. My Great Grandfather John Edward Conroy was French speaking Canadian. The only thing is I'm not sure from where. In fact that is the family mystery. We knew he left home at around age 13 and went to Michigan (where everone else in my family lives.) But he would never talk about his family until it was to late. He was on his death bed when he wanted to get word to them and things he said then were mixed up. I'm sure you are able to guess that I'm wondering if in

some way we could be related. I realize any relationship would be very distant. Its just that my father being a young boy when his name sake died has a hope of someday finding some of these "roots." Of course Dad is 60 now but he still has no idea of where to start. If you know of an Uncle or Great Uncle of yours that ran away as a child or young man could you let me know. If not could you please tell me that too. I understand that this is something you might not know anything about and I know this is an imposition on your time. But would you

Please answer. I am inclosing a self addressed stamped envelope for your convence.
Thank you for your time.
By the way your a very good writer. I say that as a reader to a writer. It would be nice to be related to such a writer even if it was a long ways off. But if we just happen to have had the same last name I still enjoyed your book.
Thank you,
Irene Conroy Hulett

William L. Hungate
9th District, Missouri
Phone: 202-223-2956
Rossetta Pagnella

January 8, 1972
Mr. Jack Conroy
701 Fisk Avenue
Moberly, Missouri 65270
Dear Mr. Conroy:
Thank you for your recent letter outlining your views on various subjects.
I am grateful to you for bringing your thoughts on these important issues to my attention and share your concern that the system of checks and balances is being weakened by the increasing assumption of power by the Executive Branch. You may rest assured that your comments will be utmost in my mind should any legislation regarding this vital matter reach the floor of the House.
In regard to your remarks on the Vietnam conflict, you might be interested in knowing that on January 2, 1973 I supported a resolution in the Democratic Caucus that amounted to censure of the President for resuming bombing in North Vietnam. The resolution provided that Congress would not allow further public funds to be appropriate or spent for U.S. military operations in Indochina, contingent only on accounting for our missing in action and prisoners of war. You may rest assured that I will continue to work for a permanent solution to the conflict in South East Asia. 
Again, thank you for writing, and if I may ever be of assistance to you in the future, please to not hesitate to call upon me. 
With all my best wishes, I am
Sincerely yours,
William L. Hungate
WLH/vk/bf
[handwritten] I appreciate and value your friendship

Dear Mr. Conroy,
Thanks for the audience last week. My friend was thrilled with the inscribed copy of your book.
I enjoyed visiting Mike Wright and his family during the forth of July weekend there in Moberly, but it's good to be back in Denver where there's virtually no humidity. We're spoiled here. 
Sincerely,
Jack Conroy
701 Fisk
Moberly, MO.
65270
